Category>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G045771/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>People's faces contain large amount of information that we can access just by looking at them. For example, we can tell a person's age or sex just by looking at their face. We often remark that someone is looking healthy or ill, and often these remarks include colour words: for example, someone who looks ill might be &amp;quot;looking green&amp;quot; and someone who is looking healthy might be &amp;quot;rosy-cheeked&amp;quot;. This project examines how aspects of people's health (such as diet and exercise levels) may be reflected in the colour of their skin. The work also examines how people's skin colour affects how healthy they appear to be. A variety of techniques are used in this work: reflectance spectrophotometry allows the accurate measurement of people's skin colour and identification of pigments in their skin; perceptual experiments give insight into how colour affects perceptions of faces including judgements of health, attractiveness and dominance; questionnaires are used to identify important lifestyle factors such as their fruit and vegetable intake and exercise levels. This fellowship is allowing the researcher to publish and disseminate his findings and to learn new research techniques that will allow him to take his work in exciting new directions.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>76196</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr: